Preheat the oven to 200°C. Remove the @lamb roasting joint{450%g} from the fridge
to allow it to come up to room temperature. Pour enough @oil{} into a deep
#baking tray{} to cover the bottom and pop in the oven. Bring a large
#saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil. Peel and chop the
@potatoes{450%g} into 4cm chunks. Boil the potatoes for ~{7-8%minutes} or until
the edges are soft.

Meanwhile, pick the @mint{1%sprig} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop
(discard the stalks). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic
press{}). Pop the garlic, mint, @panko breadcrumbs{25%g}, @dried oregano{1%tsp}
and @oil{1%tbsp} for the breadcrumbs into a medium #bowl{}. Season well with
salt and pepper, then mix together and set aside.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{} and sprinkle on the
@plain flour{1%tbsp}. Shake to fluff up the potatoes, then carefully add them
to the hot baking tray, turning in the oil. Season with salt, then roast on
the top shelf until golden for ~{45-50%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

While the potatoes roast, carefully remove the lamb from the netting (discard
the netting) and place onto a baking tray. Season the lamb with salt and
pepper, then spread the @Dijon mustard{15%g} over the top. Press the herby
breadcrumbs over the mustard.

> TIP: Don't worry if any crumb falls off.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Roast the lamb on the middle shelf for ~{25-30%minutes} for medium-rare. Add
an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your lamb more well done. Wrap loosely in
#foil{} and rest for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.

> IMPORTANT: The lamb is cooked when browned on the outside.

== Butter Glazed Carrots and Peas ==

About 15 minutes before serving, pop a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.
Add the @unsalted butter{20%g}, @water{50%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} for the veg
and stir to combine. Trim and halve any large @Chantenay carrots{150%g} lengthways,
then add them to the pan. Bring to a boil, cover with a #lid{} or foil, then
lower the heat and simmer until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Remove the lid, then
add the @peas{120%g} and cook for ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring occasionally or until
the liquid has evaporated and the veg is glazed and piping hot. Season to taste,
then remove from the heat.

== Red Wine Jus ==

While the veg cooks, pop the (now empty) potato pan on medium-high heat. Pour
in the @water{300%ml} for the jus. Bring to the boil, then stir in the
@red wine jus paste{30%g}. Reduce the heat slightly, then bubble away until
the sauce has reduced by half, ~{7-8%minutes}. Once glossy and thickened,
remove from the heat.

When everything is ready, thinly slice the lamb and serve on your plates with
the potatoes and veg alongside. Spoon over the red wine jus to finish. Enjoy!